title.children: PwC's 'phoenix' restructure under scrutiny, ASX set to slip on heightened rate fears

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Labor senator Deborah O'Neill, who has led the Senate inquiry that unearthed emails detailing PwC's attempts to sell tax advice based on confidential information it gained while working for the federal government, is sceptical of the firm's attempt to split off its government consultancy business. "Very, very slow, very resistant responses to any of those public inquiries, and yet we have this unseemly haste, with a profit-driven motive, to try and phoenix itself back into some sort of connection with the government," she told Patricia Karvelas on RN Breakfast. "I'm very concerned at this point of time that the motivations of those at PwC remain self-centred and not about service." The deal will see around 130 PwC partners and 1,750 staff transferred to the new owners, Allegro. Ms O'Neill is concerned that much of the culture that led to the tax leaks scandal will be transferred with the staff. Skip to about 4 minutes into the interview to listen to the section on PwC.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Labor senator accuses PwC of trying to 'phoenix' its way back into government work

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Good morning, and welcome to another week of trade on the ASX and corporate and economic news from around the nation and the world. The ASX 200 futures are pointing towards a modest decline on the local share market, down 0.2% at 7,043 points. That's also more than 50 points below where the ASX 200 index closed on Friday. NAB economist Taylor Nugent said the interest rate outlook is still the key driver of share moves. "During the week, the BoE [Bank of England] and Norges Banks [Norway] increased rates by 50bp [basis points] amid inflation backdrops that continued to provide too little evidence of cooling. "In the US, [Federal Reserve chair Jerome] Powell reiterated the June dots for two more hikes in front of lawmakers, but that FOMC baseline continues to be discounted by markets, which price just one hike for a peak in November. "On Friday, Atlanta's Bostic, firmly at the dovish end of the FOMC spectrum, said that 'I'd be comfortable with the information I have today, staying right where we are and just staying here through the rest of this year and long into next year.' "San Francisco's Daly said that two more quarter point hikes are a "very reasonable projection" but further emphasised that that outlook is conditional on the data flow, 'we are going to have to find the terminal rate by looking at the data.'" Until it is totally clear that inflation is coming down and interest rates have definitely peaked, it seems there is more volatility in the offing. Join me for the ride.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: ASX set to slip as Wall Street traders worry about more rate rises

children.content: Good morning, and welcome to another week of trade on the ASX and corporate and economic news from around the nation and the world.
The
ASX 200 futures
are pointing towards a modest decline on the local share market,
down 0.2% at 7,043 points
. That's also more than 50 points below where the ASX 200 index closed on Friday.
NAB economist Taylor Nugent
said the interest rate outlook is still the key driver of share moves.
"During the week, the
BoE [Bank of England] and Norges Banks [Norway] increased rates by 50bp [basis points]
amid inflation backdrops that continued to provide too little evidence of cooling.
"In the US, [Federal Reserve chair Jerome] Powell reiterated the June dots for
two more hikes
in front of lawmakers, but that FOMC baseline continues to be discounted by markets, which price just one hike for a peak in November.

"On Friday, Atlanta's Bostic, firmly at the dovish end of the FOMC spectrum, said that 'I'd be comfortable with the information I have today, staying right where we are and just staying here through the rest of this year and long into next year.'

"San Francisco's Daly said that two more quarter point hikes are a "very reasonable projection" but further emphasised that that outlook is conditional on the data flow, 'we are going to have to find the terminal rate by looking at the data.'"

Join me for the ride.
